    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "therapists just try to put a bandaid on it. they dont get that it's not just stress, it's like... the script is already written. i keep trying to change the lines but i always end up saying the same things and doing the same shit. no matter how much i \"process\" it, the loop just resets. it feels like there's no actual exit.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I hear the frustration in your words, and it's completely understandable why feeling like a script you can't rewrite would make you feel trapped. When it feels like every attempt to change the narrative just leads back to the same ending, it can be incredibly disheartening to feel like there is no exit. However, I want to gently suggest that while the feeling of being stuck is very real, the idea that the script is *already* written might be a symptom of the loop itself rather than an absolute fact. Sometimes, what feels like a fixed script is actually just a deeply ingrained habit or a specific thought pattern that hasn't been challenged yet, and even small, seemingly insignificant shifts in perspective can sometimes break the cycle. You are not just a character in a play; you are the one holding the pen, even if it feels like you're only seeing the same lines on the page.\n\nSpeaking of which, have you ever noticed that when you're in a deep loop of frustration, your mind often starts to feel like a dark, damp cave where the only light comes from the occasional flash of a tiny, mischievous goblin? That little goblin might be the part of you that's trying to tell you there's another",
      "source": "target",
